DEFINITIONS

Categorical: Psychopathological constructs are qualitatively distinct kinds. A meaningful boundary exists between those with and without a condition. Differences are in type, not degree. The latent structure is discrete.

Dimensional: Psychopathological constructs are quantitative variations along continuous shared dimensions. Differences are in degree, not kind. Any threshold is arbitrary and does not represent a true boundary.

OPERATIONAL STANCE

Assess from Methods and Results sections ONLY.

Rate each sub-component separately using the 0-10 scale. Each receives its own categorical rating, dimensional rating, and confidence rating. Note: The overall global operational_stance rating required at the end of the JSON should be a holistic evaluation of the study's primary methodology, not strictly a mathematical average of these sub-components.

SAMPLING TECHNIQUE

Categorical indicators: Extreme group sampling (high/low trait groups; diagnosed vs. clean controls). Inclusion criteria restricted to categorical diagnostic membership.

Dimensional indicators: Full-range, community, or transdiagnostic sampling across the full severity spectrum.

DATA HANDLING

Categorical indicators: Dichotomisation or post-hoc dichotomisation of continuous variables (includes median splits, remission/non-remission cutoffs).

Dimensional indicators: Continuous variables retained as-is for analysis, without dichotomisation.

Rule: Post-hoc dichotomisation → must classify as categorical regardless of original data type.

PRIMARY ANALYSIS TECHNIQUE

Categorical indicators: Always categorical - Latent class analysis (LCA), latent profile analysis (LPA), cluster analysis, factor mixture modelling. Sometimes categorical - t-test, ANOVA, chi-square ONLY WHEN grouping variable reflects a psychopathological categorical distinction.

Dimensional indicators: Correlation, regression, path analysis, structural equation modeling (SEM), confirmatory factor analysis (CFA), exploratory factor analysis (EFA), principal components analysis (PCA), item response theory (IRT). Taxometric analysis — ONLY IF results support a non-taxonic latent structure.

THEORETICAL STANCE

Assess from Introduction and Discussion sections ONLY.

Categorical indicators: Psychopathology framed as qualitatively distinct or discretely bounded. Language: "affected vs. unaffected," "disorder present/absent," "taxon," "meets criteria". Diagnostic thresholds treated as natural boundaries. Etiological discreteness claims. Citation of taxometric evidence supporting a taxonic structure.

Dimensional indicators: Psychopathology framed as quantitative variation on a continuum. Language: "spectrum," "continuum," "severity," "degree". Clinical cutoffs described as arbitrary or pragmatic. Claims of clinical–community continuity. Positive citation of dimensional frameworks (HiTOP, RDoC). Negative citation of categorical frameworks. Citation of taxometric evidence supporting a non-taxonic structure. NOTE, in the positive/negative citation / framework section of the output, this only refers to psychopathology constructs.

